<font color="#FF0000">CHRISMAS 1971...</font><br>
<tt>Sun Dec 14  6:42:54 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Christmas 1971, one remember forever.<br><br>
Christmas 1971 found me back in the world, in a small town in the state  of Mass, little town at the jct. of Rt20 &amp; I495 I had left this town when I was drafted into the service and now it was  my first Christmas back in the cradle of liberty &amp; freedom. I had found a place to stay, seems that no matter how hard I trying no  one would rent an Apt to a returning Baby-burner. Every Apt I tried to  rent wanted to know my draft status and once they found out I had returned from Vietnam.. well that apt really is not for rent yet, or they needed three months deposit or some other lame excuse. But I had found shelter, if one could call it that in what a scum land_lord called an Apt under the local Pizza joint... the one at the west end of town on Rt20.. the one with a WAR memorial monument there at the Y in the road. The Apt if you could call it that was in the basement, only access to the place was from the rear. Two rooms, sand stone walls and dirt floors. One bare 100 watt bulb from the ceiling provided the  lighting day and night, no switch to turn it on or off, no windows,no heat save for the pizza oven one floor up. Only palce to sleep was an anry cot I had found at salvation army.. alomg with some wool green army blankets, it still got very cold down there. Not as cold as my heart was  becoming though. The Day before X-mas the local police towed off my 1963  piece of sh*t VW.. they called it a derelict vech.. yea it was but at $50 for the car it was all I could put out for a car. It cost me another $25 to get the car back but the local police had another suprize for me, seems there was a warrant out on me for failure to report for jury duty two years ago, while I was hip deep in mud in Vietnam. First I had heard of it. Almost spent X-mas  in their little jail. Only reason they let me go I believe to this day was they just didn't want anyone in their jail seeing how they could not pawn me off to any other town for holding till they could get me to court after x-mas. I spent Christmas eve walking the streets of this pretty little town looking at the Christmas lights and passing home after home seeing expensive X-mas trees all light up, people sitting down to a big x-mas dinner the local greasy spoon was closed that evening and after the police had let me go.. it was closed for the holidays... The place I worked had tried to give me a 18 lb turkey days before for the holidays.. A present from the Pres. of the company. He himself stood in the back of a trailer and gave those turkeys out to his workers as they went home. He was a little upset with me because I would not take one. I am Sorry Mr Olsin I should have explained.  I watched as familles drove to church that night and their descustd looks as they saw me on the street After a while I noticed that the police cruisers seemed to be looking for someone,  wonder how many people had call them to bitch that I was on the streets ? Peace on earth &amp; good will to all men, only works in this town if those men have enough money to be of an equal economic standard as thou, or many it was if they were not  baby-burning scum of Vietnam Veterans... wonder which it was.. or both ?  The real hypocrisy of it all was that in house after house their burnt a single  bulb candle, a light in the window. Started during WWII when some one's husband,son went off to war and the light in the window burnt 'round the clock till their service man came home. Many of those bulbs have burnt since then.. for their man who did not come home and all the others who did not come home. Some how standing in the cold that night seeing those candles hardened my heart.. I WAS HOME DAMNIT ! Or was it that because Vietnam was not a GOOD war the light in the window was not for me ? <br><br>
 I will NEVER forget, nor forgive for my first Christmas home. But I ask not for pity, nor sadness save that for the people of the town of Marlboro Mass... they are the ones who truly deserve it. I want to thank them for the lesson that holiday season, that I was not then nor ever home, thanks to those who help harden their hearts by spitting on me &amp; calling me every vile name in the book. You  only made me harder of heart and mind than I already was. I had let down my guard upon coming home, no need to fear charlie any more no fear and being scared to being killed. No reason for I was already dead in your hearts. Hell even the enemy in Vietnam had more respect for me than you showed me that season of good will to all men. So as you drive to church this x-mas eve remember the spit upon Grunt who walked your streets that night, and have a nice holiday season I shall and a long way from your little town.<br><br>
A Vietnam Veteran Who will always remember...<br><br>
PS: Turn off the single candle in the window, you would not know him if he came home anyway..
